# Stackfax OpenClaw 4.29 Field Notes

This file captures Stackfax field notes from OpenClaw 4.29 and related public release/community signals.

The goal is not to document every technical detail.

The goal is to identify what OpenClaw 4.29 may change about Ai stack fit, active-run control, memory governance, communication accountability, subagent routing, follow-up commitments, update risk, and recheck timing.

This is Stackfax interpretation, not official OpenClaw documentation.

---

## Source Note

Public release sources for OpenClaw 2026.4.29 highlight active-run steering, visible-reply enforcement, spawned subagent routing metadata, opt-in follow-up commitments, people-aware memory wiki behavior, provenance views, Active Memory filters, partial recall on timeout, and bounded REM preview diagnostics.

Stackfax treats these as stack-fit signals, not as implementation guarantees.

---

## Core Takeaway

OpenClaw 4.29 appears to be a control-layer update.

The biggest signal is not simply that agents got smarter.

The bigger signal is that agents appear to be getting more steerable, more memory-aware, more communication-visible, and more operationally accountable.

That makes Stackfax more relevant, not less relevant.

When agents can be steered mid-run, remember people, route subagents, send visible replies, and create follow-up commitments, the stack needs stronger governance.

The question is no longer only:

> Can the agent do the task?

The better Stackfax question is:

> Who can steer it, what can it remember, what can it promise, where can it reply, and what receipt proves what happened?

---

## Stackfax Translation

OpenClaw 4.29 signals a shift from setup friction toward operational control.

A maturing agent platform creates more need for:

- steering policies
- communication boundaries
- memory governance
- follow-up controls
- subagent routing receipts
- run receipts
- permission checks
- rollback plans
- recheck logic
- human approval gates

Keeper line:

> A steerable agent still needs a steering policy.

Another keeper:

> When agents can remember people and promise follow-ups, memory and commitments become governance problems.

