## Major Stackfax Signals

### 1. Active-Run Steering

OpenClaw 4.29 appears to make active-run steering a stronger default behavior for messaging and automation flows.

Stackfax signal:

If an agent can be steered while it is already working, the stack needs rules for who can steer it and what kind of steering is allowed.

Possible Stackfax categories:

- Active-Run Steering Risk
- Intervention Policy Needed
- Operator Control Layer
- Mid-Run Instruction Risk
- Human Override Required
- Run Receipt Required

Useful line:

A steerable agent still needs a steering policy.

Stackfax questions:

- Who is allowed to interrupt or redirect the run?
- Are mid-run instructions logged?
- Can steering override the original task?
- Can steering expand permissions?
- Does the final receipt show what changed mid-run?
- Does the agent pause before risky redirected actions?

---

### 2. Visible-Reply Enforcement

OpenClaw 4.29 appears to highlight visible-reply enforcement for messaging.

Stackfax signal:

If an agent can reply through a communication channel, users need proof of what it said, where it said it, and why.

Possible Stackfax categories:

- Communication Channel Risk
- Visible Reply Required
- Accidental Send Risk
- Message Boundary Risk
- Public Reply Risk
- Run Receipt Required

Useful line:

If the agent can talk, the receipt should show where it talked.

Stackfax questions:

- Which channel did the agent reply in?
- Was the reply visible to the right people?
- Could the agent reply publicly by mistake?
- Does the run receipt capture the message?
- Was human approval required before sending?
- Can the agent distinguish draft, private, and public replies?

---

### 3. Spawned Subagent Routing Metadata

OpenClaw 4.29 appears to include stronger metadata for spawned subagent routing.

Stackfax signal:

Multi-agent handoffs need receipts.

If work passes between agents, the stack needs visibility into which subagent handled which part and why.

Possible Stackfax categories:

- Subagent Routing Risk
- Multi-Agent Handoff Receipt
- Responsibility Boundary Needed
- Agent Coordination Risk
- Routing Visibility Missing
- Evaluation Layer Needed

Useful line:

Agents do not become a team until responsibility moves through a durable handoff.

Stackfax questions:

- Which subagent was spawned?
- What task was handed off?
- Why was that subagent chosen?
- What context did it receive?
- What did it return?
- Did the parent agent verify the result?
- Did the run receipt preserve the handoff?

---

### 4. Follow-Up Commitments

OpenClaw 4.29 appears to add opt-in follow-up commitments for heartbeat-delivered reminders.

Stackfax signal:

When an agent can promise to follow up later, commitments become part of governance.

A follow-up is not just a reminder.

It is a future action path.

Possible Stackfax categories:

- Commitment Governance Risk
- Reminder Boundary Needed
- Follow-Up Approval Required
- Spam Risk
- Customer Contact Risk
- Owner Review Needed

Useful line:

A reminder becomes risk when it can contact the outside world.

Stackfax questions:

- What did the agent promise to follow up on?
- Who receives the follow-up?
- Is the follow-up internal or external?
- Can the follow-up send messages automatically?
- Is there a human review step before contact?
- Can the user cancel or edit the commitment?
- Does the system show all pending commitments?

---

### 5. People-Aware Memory Wiki

OpenClaw 4.29 appears to expand memory into a people-aware wiki with provenance views and per-conversation Active Memory filters.

Stackfax signal:

Memory is becoming relationship infrastructure.

That is powerful, but it creates new risk around provenance, boundaries, false memory, and inappropriate recall.

Possible Stackfax categories:

- People Memory Risk
- Memory Provenance Needed
- False Memory Risk
- Private Memory Risk
- Active Memory Boundary
- Relationship Context Risk

Useful line:

False memory breaks trust faster than missing memory.

Another useful line:

Memory is not automatically permission.

Stackfax questions:

- What people can the system remember?
- Where did the memory come from?
- Can the user inspect provenance?
- Can the memory be corrected or deleted?
- Is memory scoped by conversation?
- Can private relationship context leak into the wrong workflow?
- Is memory used for drafting only, or can it trigger actions?

---

### 6. Active Memory Filters

OpenClaw 4.29 appears to highlight per-conversation Active Memory filters.

Stackfax signal:

Memory scope is now a stack-design problem.

The issue is not only what the agent knows.

The issue is what the agent is allowed to bring into this specific run.

Possible Stackfax categories:

- Memory Scope Risk
- Context Boundary Needed
- State Design Needed
- Private Context Leakage
- Run-Specific Memory Policy
- Prompt Governance Risk

Useful line:

Pass state, not history.

Another useful line:

Continuity requires context discipline, not just stored facts.

Stackfax questions:

- Which memories are active for this conversation?
- Which memories are excluded?
- Who decides the memory scope?
- Does memory scope change by channel, person, or task?
- Can memory from one workflow contaminate another?
- Does the run receipt show memory/context used?

---

### 7. Partial Recall On Timeout

OpenClaw 4.29 appears to include partial recall behavior on timeout.

Stackfax signal:

Partial recall can be useful, but partial memory can also create false confidence.

A system that recalls only part of the relevant context should reveal that limitation.

Possible Stackfax categories:

- Partial Recall Risk
- Context Completeness Risk
- Confidence Boundary Needed
- Review Required
- Memory Receipt Needed

Useful line:

Partial recall should not create full-confidence output.

Stackfax questions:

- Did recall complete or time out?
- What was missing?
- Did the agent warn the user?
- Did the agent downgrade confidence?
- Did the output require review?
- Was partial recall captured in the run receipt?

---

### 8. Bounded REM Preview Diagnostics

OpenClaw 4.29 appears to include bounded REM preview diagnostics.

Stackfax signal:

Diagnostics are becoming part of the stack.

This supports Stackfax doctrine: serious Ai stacks need observability, not vibes.

Possible Stackfax categories:

- Diagnostic Layer Needed
- Memory Debugging Needed
- Evaluation Layer Needed
- Run Receipt Required
- Production Readiness Risk

Useful line:

Diagnostics turn agent behavior from mystery into evidence.

Stackfax questions:

- Can the user inspect what memory/context is being used?
- Can they preview relevant memory before the run?
- Is the preview bounded?
- Does the preview expose sensitive information?
- Does the diagnostic layer help reduce false memory?
- Does it feed the run receipt?

